<P>
 CITY OF GOD by Gil Cuadros (City Lights Books: $9.95; 150 pp., paperback 
original) and THE LISTENER by Bo Huston (Saint Martin's Press: $8.95; 168 pp.). 
Two young authors use fiction to examine life with AIDS. The hard-edged stories 
and poems by Cuadros capture the triple alienation of being Hispanic, gay and 
HIV-positive in contemporary L.A. "Chivalry," a sharply observed vignette of a 
minority within a minority, contrasts poignantly with "Reynaldo," a study of 
love denied. This talented author reminds the reader that the sand in the 
hourglass is flowing faster than it should in "At Risk:" "I didn't dare ask how 
long I've got,/ palm over my mouth,/ I say mother/ softer than I ever did 
before." The title novella in the collection by Bo Huston focuses on a 
photographer who retreats to an isolated house on the California coast, seeking 
a respite from the illness and death of so many friends. 
</P>
