</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 TIGER'S DESTINY by Valmik Thapar, photographs by Fateh Singh Rathore and 
Mahipal Singh (Trafalgar Square: $22.95; 176 pp.) . Thapar traces the spread of 
the tiger through Asia at the end of the last Ice Age, and the hunting and 
environmental degradation that have decimated the elegant felines. A shrinking 
population is now largely restricted to small, isolated preserves, including 
Ranthambhore National Park in north-central India, where the arresting 
photographs of tigers hunting, resting, rearing cubs, etc. were taken. Although 
the recent CITES meeting produced a ban on the traffic in tiger parts, Thapar's 
unhappy conclusion is that the tiger may soon cease to burn bright in the 
forest of the night. 
</P>
