<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORE SAN FRANCISCO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 My husband and I are third-generation Californians, born and raised in San 
Francisco, and when we travel to our favorite city to visit friends and 
relatives, we also go there to eat at our favorite restaurants. I cannot 
understand how S. Irene Virbila recommends mostly French restaurants and 
eliminates the excellent Italian places ("Where Should I Eat?" Oct. 16).Also, 
in selecting the Top 10 why not mention Tadich's (best seafood restaurant) or 
one of the many excellent Chinese restaurants? For travelers with just three 
nights, don't make it mostly French, even though Virbila loves it! 
</P>
<P>
 JACKLYN COOK 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Ana 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 There's an audiotape guide to San Francisco that your readers might like to 
know about. It's one of four -- the others cover the Monterey Peninsula and the 
Napa and Sonoma valleys. Prices start at $11.95, plus tax and shipping. Contact 
Rider's Guide, 484 Lake Park Ave., Suite 255, Oakland, Calif. 94610; tel. (510) 
653-2553. 
</P>
<P>
 ADRIENNE MOSER 
</P>
<P>
 Ojai 
</P>
