<HEADLINE>
<P>
PANHANDLERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Evanston, Ill., effort to wipe out panhandlers by "warning" or "advising" 
donors ("City Uses 'Interveners' to Thwart Panhandlers," Nov. 24) reminds me of 
an incident a year ago when I -- as usual -- handed a dollar bill to a 
panhandler on Telegraph Avenue in Berkeley. As we walked away, I told my 
companion, "Well, I may have been taken, but if he decides to buy drugs or 
booze with it, so be it."Twenty minutes later, coming back to my car, I spotted 
the bearded young man sitting on the curb, gnawing a huge turkey drumstick 
outside a cafeteria with a sign in its window: "Drumsticks, 95 special." 
</P>
<P>
 I would rather be taken 30 times than miss giving my dollar to a hungry man. 
</P>
<P>
 MIMI MERRILL 
</P>
<P>
 Ridgecrest 
</P>
