<HEADLINE>
<P>
IRVINE MAKES IT TWO IN A ROW, 73-70 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN WEYLER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Like a toddler taking its first tentative steps, UC Irvine was alternately 
swaggering and staggering Saturday night, but the Anteaters clung to a 73-70 
victory over the University of San Diego in front of 1,767 in the campus Sports 
Center gymnasium. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the first time in almost a year that the Anteaters (2-2) have won two 
in a row. And it's a streak that might have been three had they been able to 
make a free throw in the final seconds of regulation last week against 
14th-ranked Ohio University. 
</P>
<P>
 "We were in the exact same situation tonight as we were against Ohio and the 
difference was that this time we made one of the free throws," Coach Rod Baker 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Against the Bobcats, freshman Kevin Simmons missed the front end of a 
one-and-one situation and Irvine lost in overtime. Against San Diego, senior 
Mark Odsather made one of two free throws with seven seconds remaining and Zuri 
Williams blocked David Fizdale's three-point attempt at the buzzer. 
</P>
<P>
 "That was a monster game for us," Baker said. "It's a win on the road against 
a good team. If we're ever going to be any good, we have to win these." 
</P>
<P>
 Irvine, which began the game shooting 63% from the line, made 14 of 18 free 
throws in the final 7:14. 
</P>
<P>
 The Anteaters seemed to have command of the game when Williams made one of two 
free throws to put the Anteaters ahead, 71-64, with 24 seconds remaining. But 
Doug Harris, who made four of six three-pointers and led the Toreros (3-2) with 
23 points, made a three over Williams' outstretched arm with 17 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
 Khalid Channell, who had nine points and eight rebounds, made a free throw to 
give Irvine a 72-67 advantage with 15 seconds remaining, but Sean Flannery made 
a shot from about a yard beyond the three-point stripe to cut the Anteaters' 
lead to two with seven seconds remaining. 
</P>
<P>
 "After I missed the first free throw, I was thinking, 'Oh, no, another Ohio 
U.,' " Odsather said. "But I was determined to make them have to make one from 
20 feet instead of two feet to get this one into overtime." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
