<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROP. 187 'FLU' WOULD GET ATTENTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What impact on the local economy would result if up to 25% of the population 
stayed home from work one day? Or didn't buy anything for a single day? 
</P>
<P>
 That's exactly the goal of a nonviolent demonstration being called for on 
Monday, when the Latino communities of Orange County, Montebello and other 
areas are mounting a "187 Flu Brownout." 
</P>
<P>
 This grass-roots effort by native-born and immigrant groups seeks to call 
attention to the contribution of "suspects" under the litigation-shrouded 
Proposition 187. 
</P>
<P>
 The move has gained encouragement far beyond the Latino community, with labor, 
civic and business, black and Asian groups supporting it. 
</P>
<P>
 On Monday, who will wash our cars, prepare our restaurant meals, clean our 
offices and hospitals, maintain the nuts and bolts of Orange County's tourist 
industry? 
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps such a grass-roots effort by a few working, taxpaying consumers is 
what's needed to show their contribution to the community at-large. 
</P>
<P>
 R. DEAN WHINERY 
</P>
<P>
 Brea 
</P>
</TEXT>
