<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks and Mimi Ko 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 NOT RAM ENOUGH: As the Los Angeles Rams count down (maybe) till departing for 
other pastures, have you wondered how they've fared since they became an 
Anaheim team in 1980? Right now for those 15 years they're at 109-120 -- with 
no Super Bowl appearances under the Big A banner. . . . The Rams -- 4-9 so far 
this season -- try to improve their numbers against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers 
today (C10). You can catch the game on TV at 10 a.m., Channel 11. 
</P>
<P>
 PARTY POOPER? The police become a worry if you party too loudly. But in 
Newport Beach -- if Police Chief Robert J. McDonell gets his way -- you'd 
better worry if one of your renters parties a little too much. McDonell 
presents to the City Council on Monday a report recommending civil fines for 
either renters or owners of homes where the police are called to quiet a party. 
. . . Owners could be fined as much as $300 if the police have to make repeated 
disturbance calls within a year to the same address. 
</P>
<P>
 WALE OF A NIGHT: If you're doing an evening of Welsh Christmas performances, 
you have to start with famous Welsh writer Dylan Thomas. His "Child's Christmas 
in Wales" will be read during "A Welsh Christmas" at the Garden Grove 
Historical Society, 12174 Euclid Ave., tonight and Monday at 7:30. . . . The 
show features many cast members from the old Grove Shakespeare, such as Danny 
Oberbeck, above. That Shakespeare troupe had put on the Dylan Thomas story each 
Christmas for seven years. 
</P>
<P>
 HEAD OF HER CLASS: It was grad night for a class of one last week at Brea 
Canyon High School. District board members signed the diploma for Marlo Ortiz, 
who completed her course work through approved independent study. . . . Ortiz 
says it was important that she graduate before Dec. 15, when she turns 19: "I 
had a goal to be out before my birthday. This is my birthday present to 
myself." School officials couldn't remember any other student graduating early 
like that, but praised her for meeting her goal and wished her well. 
</P>
