<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SOUTH: SOUTH-CENTRAL; ROYAL VISITORS FROM AFRICA MEET RESIDENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Linking the past to the future was what Dolores Sheen Blunt had in mind when 
she brought two village chiefs and a queen from the West Africa nation of Ghana 
to visit African Americans in South-Central. 
</P>
<P>
 "I want children to understand that America is their country and (Africa) is 
their homeland," said Blunt, principal of Sheenway School and Cultural Center, 
a private facility in Watts. "We need to get their wisdom. We need to record 
it. It's not in our history books. They are living history." 
</P>
<P>
 Chief Togbui Nukpe II of the Ewe tribe and Ga tribe leaders Chief Kii Okuley 
II and Queen Mother Naa Ashami offered insight Dec. 2 into their way of life in 
their respective coastal tribes. At the same time, they were given a window 
into the lives of area residents. 
</P>
<P>
 "We saw life in Los Angeles, which is very similar to that of Ghana," said the 
village chiefs and queen through interpreter Alexander Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've not seen sad things since we've been here," he said, referring to the 
crime and violence the area has been linked with in some circles. 
</P>
<P>
 The cultural exchange, funded by the African-American Business Assn., also 
celebrated Blunt's ambitious plan to open a Sheenway school in Ghana by early 
next year in Nukpe's farming village of 3,000 residents. The royal entourage, 
as well as a team of Sheenway officials led by Blunt, left for Ghana last week 
to inspect the locale of the new school. 
</P>
<P>
 "This link will boost the self-esteem of kids here," said Blunt, who traces 
her heritage to Ghana. "In return, we will be giving back to Africa what was 
taken away." 
</P>
<P>
 Raised in South-Central Los Angeles, Dondre Bausley, 27, said having access to 
people that are a direct connection to his past opened his eyes to his cultural 
heritage. 
</P>
<P>
 "It gave me hope that they care and they want us to care," Bausley said while 
sampling Ghanaian red beans and rice at a cultural celebration honoring the 
royal entourage at the Christian Community Center in South-Central. "It's 
refreshing to know that they want unity just as much as us." 
</P>
</TEXT>
